arch:property.oc:show_val: Sedimentation and fill of an ashy layer.

Phase X: Site abandonment post major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. Secondary destruction levels occur with the building of intercolumnar walls between the southern columns of the East Colonnade. Parts of the Lower Temenos are converted into areas for industrial activity including the use of the East and West Exedrae for lime manufacture. North of the West Exedra, a large raised platform is constructed from reused limestone and sandstone architectural fragments.

This is a fine ashy layer (Munsell 2/1 10 YR Â– black) with large quantities of architectural fragments, bone, pottery, and ceramic tiles. It is found primarily in the center of the trench, and fades out to the north. The sediment is largely ash with charcoal and burnt residue as well. The amount of burnt material, as well as hypocaust tiles and the presence of flue pipes in the associated ash layer from Trench 79 (locus 3) suggests that this may be the result of purposeful dumping of detritus from the neighboring Bath complex. The architectural fragments are probably from the original 363 collapse, and the dumped ash simply settled down around the collapsed material. This dumping could have occurred during the same period as the industrial reuse of the area, evidenced in East and West Exedra.
